The divisibility rule for 3 states that if the sum of the digits of a number is divisible by 3, then the number itself is also divisible by 3. For this problem we need to find the value of $A$ which when added with the other digits will be divisible by 3.
\begin{align*}
3 + A + 6 + 7 + 9 + 2
\end{align*}

We can see that this sum is equal to 
\begin{align*}
27 + A\\
\implies 27+A \equiv 0\mod3\\
\implies A \equiv 0 \mod 3.
\end{align*}Thus, the largest digit $A$ which makes the six-digit integer divisible by 3 is $\boxed{\textbf{(9)}}$.
